pouch boundary-line patch 0001 - the Thylacine syscall seam.

Phase 6 sub-chunk 4 (pouch-syscall-seam). Retargets musl's aarch64 syscall
seam from the Linux ABI to the Thylacine ABI. Four files, one change.

  arch/aarch64/bits/syscall.h.in  the syscall-number table. Eight calls
      that map 1:1 onto a native Thylacine syscall get the Thylacine
      number; every other macro gets 0xFFFF, the unimplemented-syscall
      sentinel. Reproduce after a musl re-vendor with this awk filter run
      over the pristine arch/aarch64/bits/syscall.h.in:

        BEGIN { m["exit"]="0"; m["exit_group"]="0"; m["read"]="9";
                m["write"]="10"; m["close"]="11"; m["mlockall"]="16";
                m["getrandom"]="20"; m["set_tid_address"]="36"; }
        /^#define __NR_/ { n=$2; sub(/^__NR_/,"",n);
            printf "#define __NR_%s %s\n", n, (n in m)?m[n]:"0xFFFF";
            next; }
        { print }

  arch/aarch64/syscall_arch.h     the non-cancellable syscall mechanism.
      Each __syscall0..6 short-circuits the 0xFFFF sentinel to -ENOSYS
      before issuing `svc`, so no foreign syscall number reaches the kernel
      (P-1) and an un-retargeted call is a clean ENOSYS (P-3).

  src/thread/__syscall_cp.c       the cancellable syscall path. __syscall_cp
      is the C chokepoint for every cancellation-point syscall; its asm
      backend __syscall_cp_asm carries no sentinel guard, so the same
      0xFFFF -> -ENOSYS check is enforced in __syscall_cp itself. (A
      seam-natured change to a src/thread/ file - not thread semantics.)

  src/internal/syscall_ret.c      the errno decoder. Thylacine signals an
      error with a flat -1 (no errno channel); pouch maps that to the
      generic EIO, and passes an explicit -errno in [-4095,-2] through. A
      _Static_assert here pins the sentinel value across the seam files.

Binding design: docs/POUCH-DESIGN.md sections 5 + 5.1. Invariants P-1, P-3.

